Sam milanista or ja sam milanista

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128923003
It depends on the context, you can rephrase it so that it's not necessary.

Ja sam milanista.
Milanista sam.

Both are correct, if its the entire sentence then you would use the first example typically. You would use the second example if there was a comma and the sentence was followed with something else. It's a complex language, especially when you get into vernacular and modern informal conversational form.

>>128918779

At least at Dominican Republic and Venezuela. both of them hugely care about it.

Puerto rico used to care about it, but their league was so screwed by the American college and draft system that their league almost died a few years ago and now they don't care so much about it.

Mexico care about it within the bounds of their love of baseball (Remember that they care more about soccer) but because Mexico is the most economically powerful of the participating countries, they have the best structure and stadiums.

Cubans do care enough when they are not too busy caring about not starving to death.

Panama is so irrelevant at the sporting level that this kind of event is one of the few where they can stand out so they do care. the same goes for Curacao.

Colombia simply don't care about it, baseball is a niche sport there. Not even in the top 5 sports there

Still, it's more important for all of them to win the national league than the caribbean series. This is a somewhat friendly event because theres no big rivalries between teams

- The cars themselves should be uprated WRC2/R2 with only a slightly more aero, and opened up turbo restrictors, to end up with 100-125 more hp. Low downforce high power cars

posts.com: I’m gonna keep this short and sweet: Caleb is kicking David's ass. Maybe this new \Plant is a real thing, or perhaps he’ll keep being the elusive leaf in the wind we know him as. Regardless, the feet-of-stone Benavidez is losing come March. First off: Plant is arguably the most slick fight today, with Haney following second. He was only stopped by Canelo because of Canelo’s ability to cut the ring and pin slimy opponents down. Both traits Benavidez lacks. Coupled with the fact that Plant cannot stay on the ropes, even if a gun was held to his head, Benavidez has no chance. Against Dirrell, David struggled to deal with him, unless Dirrell decided to fight with him or stayed on the ropes for too long, BOTH things that will NEVER happen in the large ring Plant and David is fighting in. Next, I wanna move onto something a little less objective, and more speculative: Plant’s newfound tree-like power. Plant, before and after the Dirrell fight, testified that he’s rooting his feet down like an oak tree. That claim was backed by the nasty KO Plant fed Dirrell. After that knockout, I have no choice but to believe Plant, and trust in his middleweight power. Consider this: David has been knocked down and hurt by a flimsy get-off-me left hook. Imagine David taking a serious, body-burying shovel hook similar to the one gifted to Dirrell. Do you think he’d get up? Especially after getting outboxed and taunted for 8 rounds straight? The answer is no. The glass chinned Bena CANNOT take a hook like that Plant. In summary, we know that inorder to beat Plant, you need to be able to cut the ring well, pin the gliding leaf down, and hit hard AND in rapid volume. David has none of that. To beat DB, you need to be an elusive monster, not staying on the ropes for more than a microsecond. Alternatively, you can feed him a hard hook or two. Plant can do both. To believe Benavidez can defeat Plant is to believe Benavidez is on the same level as Canelo, but that is not the case.

Coupled with the fact that Plant cannot stay on the ropes, even if a gun was held to his head, Benavidez has no chance. Against Dirrell, David struggled to deal with him, unless Dirrell decided to fight with him or stayed on the ropes for too long, BOTH things that will NEVER happen in the large ring Plant and David is fighting in. Next, I wanna move onto something a little less objective, and more speculative: Plant’s newfound tree-like power. Plant, before and after the Dirrell fight, testified that he’s rooting his feet down like an oak tree. That claim was backed by the nasty KO Plant fed Dirrell. After that knockout, I have no choice but to believe Plant, and trust in his middleweight power. Consider this: David has been knocked down and hurt by a flimsy get-off-me left hook. Imagine David taking a serious, body-burying shovel hook similar to the one gifted to Dirrell. Do you think he’d get up? Especially after getting outboxed and taunted for 8 rounds straight? The answer is no. The glass chinned Bena CANNOT take a hook like that Plant. In summary, we know that inorder to beat Plant, you need to be able to cut the ring well, pin the gliding leaf down, and hit hard AND in rapid volume. David has none of that. To beat DB, you need to be an elusive monster, not staying on the ropes for more than a microsecond. Alternatively, you can feed him a hard hook or two. Plant can do both. To believe Benavidez can defeat Plant is to believe Benavidez is on the same level as Canelo, but that is not the case.
